-- ── Chisel ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$This profile covers Chisel.app, the product management and roadmapping platform, not the unrelated open-source project also named chisel, which is a Go-based TCP/UDP tunneling tool over HTTP. Chisel (Chisel Labs) unified roadmapping, customer feedback collection, and cross-functional team alignment in one app for product managers, and added an AI PM agent for drafting PRDs, release notes, and feedback triage. Founded in 2020 and headquartered in San Francisco with engineering in Pune, India, Chisel Labs was acquired by product-experience platform Pendo in February 2026, and its technology and team are now being folded into Pendo's agentic AI roadmap rather than operating as a fully independent product.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (historically free-forever core tier plus paid add-ons; terms may be changing post-acquisition)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid add-ons previously started around $49 to $79/month per account)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Small startup team prior to 2026; now part of Pendo, a larger company, following the February 2026 acquisition$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States, with an engineering team in Pune, India$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Chisel Review: Product Roadmap Software (Acquired by Pendo in 2026)$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Chisel was a product management and roadmapping tool with AI features, acquired by Pendo in 2026. See its features, pricing history, and what changed.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$The name Chisel is shared by two unrelated software products, so it is worth clarifying upfront which one this profile covers. This is Chisel.app, also known as Chisel Labs, a product management and roadmapping platform, and it is not the same as the open-source project also called chisel, a Go-based command-line tool for tunneling TCP and UDP traffic over HTTP, which serves a completely different, network-engineering audience. Chisel Labs was founded in 2020 and built its product around a specific complaint from product managers: that roadmapping, customer feedback collection, and cross-functional team alignment usually lived in three or more disconnected tools, spreadsheets, and slide decks. Chisel's platform combined agile, customizable roadmaps (with kanban, release, and timeline views) with a feature called Team Radar, designed to surface where stakeholders across an organization agreed or disagreed on priorities so disagreements could be resolved proactively rather than discovered late. On the feedback side, an IdeaBox let teams capture, curate, and prioritize feature ideas and requests from multiple sources, while a Customer Portal and built-in surveys gave customers a dedicated space to submit feedback and track progress on requests they cared about. More recently, Chisel added an AI PM agent capable of drafting product requirement documents (PRDs) and release notes, summarizing user research, triaging incoming feedback, and flagging anomalies in a roadmap automatically, aiming to save product managers meaningful hours each week on repetitive documentation work. The platform integrated with a broad set of tools common in product organizations, including Jira, Azure DevOps, Salesforce, Zendesk, Intercom, GitHub, Amplitude, Mixpanel, Confluence, and Microsoft Teams, plus thousands more through Zapier. Historically, Chisel's pricing followed a free-forever model for core roadmapping and team alignment features, with paid add-ons, publicly reported at various points around 79 dollars per month per account for unlimited stakeholders and Jira integration, and around 49 dollars per month for customer surveys and additional integrations, though buyers should confirm current terms directly rather than assume these historical figures still apply. The most consequential recent development is that Pendo, a software experience management platform, acquired Chisel Labs on February 3, 2026, in what Pendo described as its fourth acquisition in 18 months and third acquisition of an AI-native startup, explicitly aimed at expanding Pendo's agentic AI capabilities for product teams. As part of the deal, Chisel's engineering team based in Pune, India, is becoming the foundation of Pendo's tenth global office, with plans to scale that team to 50 engineers by the end of 2026. For anyone researching Chisel today, the practical implication is that it is no longer an independently operating startup: prospective and existing customers should check directly with Pendo for current product availability, packaging, and pricing rather than relying solely on Chisel's pre-acquisition marketing, since the product's future roadmap and go-to-market are now controlled by its acquirer.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'f0ac04a4-012a-47e1-a2d0-a654ad99ade3';

